  "prompt": "What is dyarchy and when was it introduced in India?",
  "response": "Dyarchy, also known as dual government, is a system of governance where power is divided between two separate authorities. In the context of British India, dyarchy was introduced under the Government of India Act 1919, also known as the Montagu-Chelmsford Reforms.\n\nThe system of dyarchy was implemented in the provinces of British India from 1921 to 1937. Under this system, the provincial governments were divided into two sections: Reserved and Transferred subjects. Reserved subjects, which included areas like law and order, finance, and revenue, were controlled by the Governor and his executive council, which consisted of nominated members. Transferred subjects, such as education, public health, and local self-government, were managed by ministers who were chosen from among the elected members of the provincial legislative council.\n\nThe idea behind dyarchy was to gradually introduce a measure of self-governance to India while maintaining British control over critical areas of administration. However, the system faced numerous challenges and criticisms, and it was eventually abolished with the introduction of the Government of India Act 1935.",
